<?xml version='1.0' encoding='UTF-8'?>
<ecoSpold xmlns="http://www.EcoInvent.org/EcoSpold02" xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance" xsi:schemaLocation="http://www.EcoInvent.org/EcoSpold02 ../../schemas/datasets/EcoSpold02.xsd http://www.EcoInvent.org/UsedUserMasterData ../../schemas/datasets/EcoSpold02UserMasterData.xsd">
  <childActivityDataset>
    <activityDescription>
      <activity specialActivityType="0" id="8afba699-7f87-5e8f-ad60-8b7034dc6b27" activityNameId="3d6f276a-5f2d-48c9-bea9-389210bca2b1" parentActivityId="875db450-c919-4dd7-86d7-7b43046fdfda" inheritanceDepth="-1" type="1">
        <activityName xml:lang="en">propylene production, from methanol-to-propylene conversion</activityName>
        <includedActivitiesStart xml:lang="en">The activity starts with the raw materials entering the methano-to-propylene facility.</includedActivitiesStart>
        <includedActivitiesEnd xml:lang="en">The activity ends with the final products being ready for further processing or transportation at the production site gate. The dataset includes the consumption of raw materials and energy, estimated catalyst use, emissions to air and water from the process, as well as the infrastructure use. </includedActivitiesEnd>
        <generalComment>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="0">This dataset represents the production of propylene via Lurgi's methanol-to-propylene (MTP) process. Namely, this dataset covers the production of 1.00 kg of propylene as reference product, while gasoline (i.e., as C5-C10 hydrocarbons) and ethylene are also co-produced (1.08 and 0.08 kg, respectively) as by-products. This inventory is represented with an excess of electricity as valuable output due to the modularity of the auxiliary services used. Overall, the production of propylene from methanol is a net consumer of electricity.  The process includes, feedstock, materials, energy and registers all relevant direct emissions.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="1">Light olefins are crucial building blocks for the chemicals and plastics sector and are predominantly generated through steam cracking of hydrocarbons. The annual production volume of ethylene and propylene are extremely high and constitutes them as the most highly produced petrochemicals. The high production volume of light olefins is driven by a high demand, which in 2007 amounted to 115 and 73 Mt for ethylene and propylene, respectively.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="2">Notably, methanol may be used to cover part of the ethylene and propylene demand. Besides, such pathway may be appealing to decouple the production of light olefins from the petroleum feedstocks, e.g., naphtha.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="3">In this dataset, Lurgi's MTP process is described, which represents the most efficient scheme for maximizing the production of propylene, and for retaining a low coking tendency, while maintaining a very low propane and by-products yield. In this technology, propylene is produced in two steps, where methanol is first converted to dimethyl ether (at almost equilibrium mixture), and subsequently converted to propylene using a ZSM-5 catalyst (zeolite-based) in a fixed-bed reactor. A typical MTP plant may produce, along with propylene, MTP-gasoline, MTP-liquefied petroleum gas (LPG), and small quantities of ethylene.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="4">References:</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="5">Olah, G.A. (2005), Beyond Oil and Gas: The Methanol Economy. Angewandte Chemie International Edition, 44: 2636-2639. https://doi.org/10.1002/anie.200462121</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="6">Bertau, M., Offermanns, H., Plass, L., Schmidt, F., &amp; Wernicke, H. J. (Eds.). (2014). Methanol: the basic chemical and energy feedstock of the future (Vol. 1). Heidelberg: Springer.</text>
        </generalComment>
      </activity>
      <classification classificationId="28f738cc-bb73-48f8-b633-f83fb9bc5ddc">
        <classificationSystem xml:lang="en">ISIC rev.4 ecoinvent</classificationSystem>
        <classificationValue xml:lang="en">2011:Manufacture of basic chemicals</classificationValue>
      </classification>
      <geography geographyId="0c40fa1e-7d7e-11de-9ae2-0019e336be3a">
        <shortname xml:lang="en">CN</shortname>
        <comment>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="0">This inventory is modelled for China, where the coal-to- and methanol-to-propylene technology is an important technological pathway to produce propylene.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="1">According to Lv et al (2021), in 2019, 24% of propylene produced in China was supplied from methanol conversion plants. </text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="2">This activity originates from literature data, based on robust process simulation, for the conversion of methanol to propylene (MTP). Since the specific technology is modelled, the inventory is not linked to any specific geographical region. The material and energy inputs reflect well the production technology and are, therefore, considered to be valid for the chosen geography.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="3">References:</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="4">Daniel F. Rodríguez-Vallejo, Gonzalo Guillén-Gosálbez, and Benoît Chachuat ACS Sustainable Chemistry &amp; Engineering 2020 8 (8), 3072-3081 DOI: 10.1021/acssuschemeng.9b05516</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="5">2021, Lin Lv, Guobao Song, Xinyue Zhao, Jingwen Chen, Environmental Burdens of China’s Propylene manufacturing: Comparative life-cycle assessment and scenario analysis, Science of the Total Environment, 799</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="6">https://www.woodmac.com/news/can-chinas-cto-and-mto-industries-survive-the-threat-of-massive-steam-cracker-investment/, assessed in 2023-10-09.</text>
        </comment>
      </geography>
      <technology technologyLevel="3">
        <comment>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="0">In this dataset, the catalytic conversion of methanol to propylene is based on the work by Rodríguez-Vallejo et al. (2020). First, the methanol feedstock, before being fed into the dimethyl ether (DME) synthesis reactor, is pumped, and heated to the expected operating conditions. Namely, the reaction takes place at 300°C and 1.65 bar, attaining a 90% methanol equilibrium conversion that resembles typical industrial yields and conditions.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="1">Subsequently, the reactor outlet, consisting of a DME and methanol mixture, is fed into the methanol-to-propylene (MTP) reactor, filled with a ZSM-5 catalyst. In the reactor, the mixture is converted mainly to olefins, such as (1) ethylene; (2) propylene; (3) C4 olefins, (4) C5 olefins; and (v) higher hydrocarbons, ranging from C6 to C10 (such as hexene(s), heptane(s), octenes, nonene(s), and decene(s)).</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="2">The MTP reactor operates at 425°C and 1.65 bar, that ensures the high methanol/DME conversion to propylene, while the overall reaction scheme is exothermic. The released heat from the latter exothermic reactor is used in a Rankine cycle to generate electricity, which is consumed internally. Any excess of generated electricity is considered as a valuable by-product.  </text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="3">The MTP reactor outlet is then cooled to 40°C, where an aqueous and organic phase is generated, and fed into a flash unit to remove the aqueous phase. The gaseous organic phase is pressurized in a three-stage compression train, with intermediate cooling, at 28.2 bar. The compressed stream is fed into a distillation column where a mixture of C4-C10 hydrocarbons is obtained at the bottom. The top stream consists of ethylene, propylene, and water, and thus, water is removed with a second flash unit prior to the purification and separation of ethylene-propylene. The water-free stream is, finally, fed into a second distillation column where polymer-grade ethylene and propylene are obtained at the top and bottom, respectively. The condenser of the second distillation unit operates at temperatures below ambient (ca. -21°C) and thus, a cooling cycle with a R134a working fluid was considered.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="4"></text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="5"></text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="6">References:</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="7">Daniel F. Rodríguez-Vallejo, Gonzalo Guillén-Gosálbez, and Benoît Chachuat ACS Sustainable Chemistry &amp; Engineering 2020 8 (8), 3072-3081 DOI: 10.1021/acssuschemeng.9b05516</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="8">Olah, G.A. (2005), Beyond Oil and Gas: The Methanol Economy. Angewandte Chemie International Edition, 44: 2636-2639. https://doi.org/10.1002/anie.200462121</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="9">Bertau, M., Offermanns, H., Plass, L., Schmidt, F., &amp; Wernicke, H. J. (Eds.). (2014). Methanol: the basic chemical and energy feedstock of the future (Vol. 1). Heidelberg: Springer.</text>
        </comment>
      </technology>
      <timePeriod startDate="2020-01-01" endDate="2023-12-31" isDataValidForEntirePeriod="true">
        <comment>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="0">This activity originates from literature data, for conversion of methanol to propylene (MTP) published in 2020 The material and energy inputs reflect well the production technology and not expected to change significantly over the next 5 years.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="1">References:</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="2">Daniel F. Rodríguez-Vallejo, Gonzalo Guillén-Gosálbez, and Benoît Chachuat ACS Sustainable Chemistry &amp; Engineering 2020 8 (8), 3072-3081 DOI: 10.1021/acssuschemeng.9b05516</text>
        </comment>
      </timePeriod>
      <macroEconomicScenario macroEconomicScenarioId="d9f57f0a-a01f-42eb-a57b-8f18d6635801">
        <name xml:lang="en">Business-as-Usual</name>
      </macroEconomicScenario>
    </activityDescription>
    <flowData>
      <intermediateExchange id="1ff1263a-e50c-5b48-b439-80d191b47642" unitId="77ae64fa-7e74-4252-9c3b-889c1cd20bfc" variableName="BP_Electricity" amount="1.0" intermediateExchangeId="759b89bd-3aa6-42ad-b767-5bb9ef5d331d" productionVolumeAmount="18562440.0" productionVolumeMathematicalRelation="RP_PV * (BP_Electricity / RP_Propylene)">
        <name xml:lang="en">electricity, medium voltage</name>
        <unitName xml:lang="en">kWh</unitName>
        <comment xml:lang="en">This inventory is represented with an excess of electricity as valuable output due to the modularity of the auxiliary services used. Overall, the production of propylene from methanol is a net consumer of electricity. Namely, in this dataset, the heat generated by the exothermic reaction could cover the electricity requirements of the light olefins production process. However, please note that the supply of cooling at temperatures below ambient is energy intensive leading to a net input of electricity into the system.

References:
Daniel F. Rodríguez-Vallejo, Gonzalo Guillén-Gosálbez, and Benoît Chachuat ACS Sustainable Chemistry &amp; Engineering 2020 8 (8), 3072-3081 DOI: 10.1021/acssuschemeng.9b05516</comment>
